explanation:
OS_ObjectIdGetById: You must see the exact definition/implementation (or macro expansion) to determine whether it can modify the caller argument 'var_id'. If OS_ObjectIdGetById is a macro or inlined routine that performs an assignment to its 'id' parameter (or otherwise writes to the identifier passed), that would constitute modification of the function parameter in the caller.

OS_CondVarUnlock_Impl: Although called with &token (not var_id), it could be a macro or inline function that references or assigns to 'var_id' from the enclosing scope. Inspecting its definition rules out any indirect modification of the parameter inside the call.

osal_id_t (typedef): The MISRA rule distinguishes reassigning a pointer parameter (forbidden) from modifying the object pointed to (allowed). Knowing whether osal_id_t is an integer, a pointer type, or a struct is required to decide whether any writes constitute modification of the parameter itself or of a referenced object.

OS_object_token_t (typedef/struct): The token object is passed by address to callees; its type definition is needed to check for possible aliasing or macros that could use the token to indirectly modify 'var_id' (or otherwise cause parameter-modifying side-effects). It also helps verify that only the pointed-to object is modified (permitted) and not the parameter variable.
